HEADWORD: Prebendary
<hw>Preb"en*da*ry</hw> <pr>(pr⟦ecr⟧b"⟦ecr⟧n*d⟦asl⟧*r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>praebendarius</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧bendaire</ets>. See <er>Prebend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A clergyman attached to a collegiate or cathedral church who enjoys
a prebend in consideration of his officiating at stated times in the
church. See <er>Note</er> under <er>Benefice</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
3.</def> <rj><au>Hook.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A prebendaryship.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bailey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prebendaryship</ent>⟦br⟧
